column4: name is also translated "An Yeong-kil" and "An Yungkil"...active on KGS, runs gogameguru.com
900 wins, 17th nihon-ki player to do so
7d in 89, Won 1989 World Amateur Go Champs
9d in 1997, the coauthor of Learn to Play Go with Janice Kim, dean of the "Department of Baduk Studies" at Myeongji University
female, 3d in 1997, married to Yo Kagen
Has played for japan's Nihon Ki-in group since young

name also written "Hunhyun"; became pro in Korea at 9 years old, then went to Japan and became pro there in 1967....reached 9d; "has played and won more games than any other pro"..."maybe second strongest player currently, after Yi Ch'ang-ho (his student)
female; 9d (the fourth woman to reach 9d in korea); Name is also "Jo Hyeoiyeon". Devout Christian, doesn't play on Sundays.

died in 2006; "the father of Korean pro Go", traveled to Japan in 1937 to study with Kitani Minoru, founded the korean go association in 1945 (spent the war in Japan apparently).  9d in 1982, uncle of Cho Chikun and Cho Shoen.  Name is also spelled "Cho N
korean-born but always Nihon Ki-in player, 9d in 1998.  Has won Honinbo (1999), dethroning Cho CHikun's 10 consecutive titles.
9d; from Taiwan, but lived in Japan since 10 years old; Nihon Ki-in player.  Chinese name: "Zhang Xu".  Pupil of Rin Kaiho, son-in-law of Kobayashi Koichi. First pro to simultaneously hold 5 titles.
aka "Fujisawa Shuko"; turned pro in 1940, 9d in 1963, retired in 1998, died in 2009.  Uncle of Fujisawa Hosai.  Active in promoting Go in China in early 1980s.
originally Fujisawa Kuranosuke, 9d in 1949, obsessed with beating Go Seigen
clearly part of the Korean Baduk league, but no biographical info
9d in 1990, Kansai Ki-in, Hasegawa Hiro is pupil
one of the strongest players of the 1970s, won Honinbo, Meijin, Oza, Tengen.  1000 wins in official games in May 20th, 2010.  Wrote "All About Thickness" and "Dictionary of Basic Joseki".
Nihon Ki-in, teacher of Iyama Yuta
also known as Honinbo Kunwa, died 1999, influential in getting Go Seigen to come to Japan
Nihon Ki-in, 9d in 1964, once known as Iwata Masao
jujo on KGS and IGS, currently plays in Korea
Nihon Ki-in, He is responsible for discovering many new joseki!
His pupils include Okada Shinichiro, Omori Yasushi, Suzuki Isao, Nishida Terumi and Umezawa Yukari. His teachers include Kitani Minoru, died in 2004. Nihon Ki-in
In 1975 he founded the Ryokusei Academy, a go school which has produced many professional players, including Yamashita Keigo
8d in 2012, also known as Kim Jiseok
Also known by Kim Seung-joon, became 9 Dan in 2005
Also known by Kim Younghwan, Kim Yeonghwan, Kim Yong-hwan
8d in 2007, played with Nihon-Kiin in Japan
created several joseki and fuseki, Teacher of famous Japanese professionals including: Ishida Yoshio, Kato Masao, Takemiya Masaki
daughter of Kobayashi Koichi and Kitani Reiko and the granddaughter of Kitani Minoru. Kobayashi is married to Cho U. Nihon Ki-in.
one of the few Go players to have won 1,200 professional games.
9d in 1995, Nihon Ki-in, Inaba Takahiro, Adachi Toshimasa, Komatsu Daiki are his pupils.
female, 8 dan in 1985. Resident in Japan during the 1990s. Former wife of Nie Weiping 9p and mother of Kou Reibun, Nihon Kiin 4p.
9d in 2006, Nihon Ki-in, pupil of Kobayashi Koichi.
9d in 2000, the first and only Western Go Professional to ever reach 9-dan, studied with Nihon Ki-in, married to Xian-Xian Niu.
9d in 1960, Nihon Ki-in, His pupils were Ishibashi Chinami, Hanawa Yasutoki, Tokimoto Hajime, Kanno Kiyonori, and Miyashita Suzue.
pupil of Kikuchi Yasuro, Nihon Ki-in
formerly married to Kong Xiangming 8 dan. Their son Ko Reibun
called Wang Mingyuan, active in Japan, A pupil of Go Seigen
Played in Japan, brought over by Go Seigen. also known as Lin Haifeng, His pupils are Cho U, Rin Kanketsu, Rin Shien, and Fu KoBai.
now living in Korea, having lived in Japan and California. Learned under Go Seigen.
9d in 1955, teacher was Masubuchi Tatsuko.  Called inventor of myushi.
9d in 1960, His pupils were Hane Yasumasa, Yamashiro Hiroshi, Nakano Hironari, Imamura Yoshiaki, Shimamura Michiro, Shigeno Yuki, and Matsumoto Nayoko.
9d in 1981, Takagi is a pupil of Nakagawa Shinji.
9d in 1977, inventor of “cosmic style” of play, as well as sanrensei.
8d in 1999, A pupil of Nie Weiping.
9d in 1963, one of the Three Crows (together with Fujisawa Hideyuki and Suzuki Keizo)
9d in 1985, Miyagawa Fumihiko is his pupil
9d in 2003, attended go school run by Kikuchi Yasuro.
also written Yang Jaeho, and called Ryo Saigo
Also written Lee Changho, pupil of Cho HunHyun, considered one of the strongest in the world in the 90's and 00's.
Elder brother of Yi Se-tol, also goes by Lee SangHoon
no apparent information – difficult to distinguish between father and the two sons. Could be that yi sang-hun sr. and yi se-tol are the same person??
9d in 2003, also known as Lee Sedol
9d in 2011, also transliterated as Lee Yeongkyu , Lee Youngkyu, or Lee Younggu
9d in 1997, Kansai Ki-in, youngest to reach 1000 wins in Japan
9d in 1998, has played against computers recently
5d in 2007, didn't study under a particular master or go school.
